Bike Sharing¶

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and Visualization¶

By: Victor Cornejo

Introduction¶

Bike sharing systems are a new generation of traditional bike rentals where the process of signing up, renting and returning is automated. Through these systems, users are able to easily rent a bike from one location and return them to another. I analyzed bike sharing data from Washington D.C.

In this project, I performed tasks to clean, visualize, and explore the bike sharing data. I also investigated open-ended questions. These open-ended questions asked me to think critically about how the plots I created to provide insights into the data.

In this project I practiced:

  • reading plaintext delimited data into pandas
  • wrangling data for analysis
  • using EDA to learn about your data
  • making informative plots

Loading Bike Sharing Data¶

The data I explored was collected from a bike sharing system in Washington D.C.

The variables in this data frame were defined as:

Variable Description
instant record index
dteday date
season 1. spring
2. summer
3. fall
4. winter
yr year (0: 2011, 1:2012)
mnth month ( 1 to 12)
hr hour (0 to 23)
holiday whether day is holiday or not
weekday day of the week
workingday if day is neither weekend nor holiday
weathersit 1. clear or partly cloudy
2. mist and clouds
3. light snow or rain
4. heavy rain or snow
temp normalized temperature in Celsius (divided by 41)
atemp normalized "feels-like" temperature in Celsius (divided by 50)
hum normalized percent humidity (divided by 100)
windspeed normalized wind speed (divided by 67)
casual count of casual users
registered count of registered users
cnt count of total rental bikes including casual and registered

Data Preparation¶

A few of the variables that are numeric/integer actually encode categorical data. These include holiday, weekday, workingday, and weathersit. In the following sectipn, I converted these four variables to strings specifying the categories. In particular, using 3-letter labels (Sun, Mon, Tue, Wed, Thu, Fri, and Sat) for weekday. I simply used yes/no for holiday and workingday.

(Decoding weekday, workingday, and weathersit)¶

Decoding the holiday, weekday, workingday, and weathersit fields:

  1. holiday: Converted to yes and no.
  2. weekday: It turns out that Monday is the day with the most holidays. Mutated the 'weekday' column to use the 3-letter label ('Sun', 'Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', and 'Sat' ...) instead of its current numerical values. I assumed 0 would correspond to Sun, 1 to Mon and so on, in order of the previous sentence.
  3. workingday: Converted to yes and no.
  4. weathersit: I replaced each value with one of Clear, Mist, Light, or Heavy. Assuming 1 would correspond to Clear, 2 to Mist, and so on in order of the previous sentence.
In [19]:
factor_dict = {
    'holiday': {0: 'no', 1: 'yes'}, 
    'weekday': {0: 'Sun', 1: 'Mon', 2: 'Tue', 3: 'Wed', 4: 'Thu', 5: 'Fri', 6: 'Sat'}, 
    'workingday': {0: 'no', 1: 'yes'}, 
    'weathersit': {1: 'Clear', 2: 'Mist', 3: 'Light', 4: 'Heavy'}
    }

bike.replace(factor_dict, inplace=True)

Exploring the Distribution of Riders¶

I began by comparing the distribution of the daily counts of casual and registered riders.

Matplotlib and Seaborn Table of Common Functions¶

x and y are sequences of values (i.e. arrays, lists, or Series).

Function Description
plt.plot(x, y) Creates a line plot of x against y
plt.title(name) Adds a title name to the current plot
plt.xlabel(name) Adds a label name to the x-axis
plt.ylabel(name) Adds a label name to the y-axis
plt.scatter(x, y) Creates a scatter plot of x against y
plt.hist(x, bins=None) Creates a histogram of x; bins can be an integer or a sequence
plt.bar(x, height) Creates a bar plot of categories x and corresponding heights height
sns.histplot(data, x, y, hue, kde) Creates a distribution plot; data is a DataFrame; x, y are column names in data that specify positions on the x and y axes; hue is a column name in data that adds subcategories to the plot based on hue; kde is a boolean that determines whether to overlay a KDE curve
sns.lineplot(data, x, y, hue) Creates a line plot
sns.scatterplot(data, x, y, hue, size) Creates a scatter plot; size is a vector that contains the size of point for each subcategory based on hue
sns.kdeplot(x, y) Creates a kernel density estimate plot; x, y are series of data that indicate positions on the x and y axis
sns.jointplot(x, y, data, kind) Creates a joint plot of 2 variables with KDE plot in the middle and a distribution plot for each variable on the sides; kind determines the visualization type for the distribution plot, can be scatter, kde or hist

Using the sns.histplot function I created a plot that overlayed the distribution of the daily counts of bike users, using blue to represent casual riders, and green to represent registered riders. The temporal granularity of the records was daily counts.

As seen, the distribution of the registered users seems to be normal, symetrical. Whereas the casual riders distribution is bimodal and skewed to the right. I bleive this to be because registered users ride usually throghout the days, whereas casual riders could have a spike on the weekends and festive days.

However...¶

The density plots did not show how the counts for registered and casual riders vary together. Therefore I used sns.lmplot to make a scatter plot to investigate the relationship between casual and registered counts. This time, I used the bike DataFrame to plot hourly counts instead of daily counts.

The lmplot function tried to draw a linear regression line. So I colored the points in the scatterplot according to whether or not the day was a working day

There were many points in the scatter plot, so I made them small to help reduce overplotting. Also I made sure of setting fit_reg=True to generate the linear regression line.

Visualization¶

Bivariate Kernel Density Plot¶

To address overplotting, I tried visualizing the data with another technique, the bivariate kernel density estimate.

A basic kde plot of all the data is quite easy to generate. However, this plot includes both weekend and weekday data, which isn't what I wanted...

In [27]:
sns.kdeplot(x=daily_counts['casual'], y=daily_counts['registered'])
plt.title('KDE Plot Comparison of Registered vs Casual Riders');
In [28]:
# Set the figure size for the plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))

# Set 'is_workingday' to a boolean array that is true for all working_days
is_workingday = daily_counts['workingday'] == "yes"

# Bivariate KDEs require two data inputs. 
# In this case, we will need the daily counts for casual and registered riders on workdays
casual_workday = daily_counts.loc[is_workingday, 'casual']
registered_workday = daily_counts.loc[is_workingday, 'registered']

# Used sns.kdeplot on the two variables above to plot the bivariate KDE for weekday rides
sns.kdeplot(x=casual_workday, y=registered_workday, cmap='Reds', shade=False, shade_lowest=False, label='Workday')

not_workingday = daily_counts['workingday'] == "no"

# Repeat the same steps above but for rows corresponding to non-workingdays

casual_non_workday = daily_counts.loc[not_workingday, 'casual']
registered_non_workday = daily_counts.loc[not_workingday, 'registered']

# Used sns.kdeplot on the two variables above to plot the bivariate KDE for non-workingday rides
sns.kdeplot(x=casual_non_workday, y=registered_non_workday, cmap='Blues', shade=False, shade_lowest=False, label='Non-workday')

plt.title('KDE Bivariate Comparison of Registered vs Casual Riders');
plt.legend();

And Voil! The lines from each color represent a group, where the shade of each group color represents the density. And the overlaping conglomerations between registered and casual users. The scatter plot made it seem as if there was almost not relationship between the groups.

Joint Plot¶

As an alternative approach to visualizing the data, I constructed the following set of three plots where the main plot showed the contours of the kernel density estimate of daily counts for registered and casual riders plotted together, and the two "margin" plots (at the top and right of the figure) provided the univariate kernel density estimate of each of these variables.

In [29]:
sns.jointplot(data=daily_counts, x='casual', y='registered', kind='kde', color='#4184bf')
plt.suptitle("KDE Contours of Casual vs Registered Rider Count")
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9);

Understanding Daily Patterns¶

I wanted to examine the behavior of riders by plotting the average number of riders for each hour of the day over the entire dataset, stratified by rider type.

In [30]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
plt.plot(bike.groupby('hr')['casual'].mean(), label='casual')
plt.plot(bike.groupby('hr')['registered'].mean(), label='registered')
plt.title('Average Count of Casual vs Registered by Hour')
plt.xlabel('Hour of the Day')
plt.ylabel('Average Count')
plt.legend();

We can observe that registered users tend to ride mostly to commute, in the mornings and evenings. Whereas Casual users ride more during the middle of the day.

I could attempt linear regression using sns.lmplot as shown below, which hint at some relationships between temperature and proportional casual, but the plot was still fairly unconvincing.

In [35]:
sns.lmplot(data=bike, x="temp", y="prop_casual", hue="weekday", scatter_kws={"s": 20}, height=10)
plt.title("Proportion of Casual Riders by Weekday");

A better approach was to use local smoothing. The basic idea is that for each x value, I compute some sort of representative y value that captures the data close to that x value. One technique for local smoothing is "Locally Weighted Scatterplot Smoothing" or LOWESS. An example is below. The red curve shown is a smoothed version of the scatterplot.

In [36]:
from statsmodels.nonparametric.smoothers_lowess import lowess
# Make noisy data
xobs = np.sort(np.random.rand(100)*4.0 - 2)
yobs = np.exp(xobs) + np.random.randn(100) / 2.0
sns.scatterplot(xobs, yobs, label="Raw Data")

# Predict 'smoothed' valued for observations
ysmooth = lowess(yobs, xobs, return_sorted=False)
sns.lineplot(xobs, ysmooth, label="Smoothed Estimator", color='red')
plt.legend();

In this case with the bike ridership data, I wanted 7 curves, one for each day of the week. The x-axis as the temperature and the y-axis will as a smoothed version of the proportion of casual riders.

In [38]:
from statsmodels.nonparametric.smoothers_lowess import lowess

plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
for day in bike['weekday'].unique():
    day_df = bike[bike['weekday'] == day]
    y = day_df['prop_casual']
    x = day_df['temp'] * 100
    ysmooth = lowess(y, x, return_sorted=False)
    sns.lineplot(x, ysmooth, label=day)
plt.title('Temperature vs Casual Rider Proportion by weekday')
plt.xlabel('Temperature (Farhenheit)')
plt.ylabel('Casual Rider Proportion')
plt.legend();

Interesting to see that the proportion of casual riders seems to pick up since Thursday through Sunday, specially in the periods where the Temperature is between 45 to 75. During the weekdays, the proportion seemed to remain constant.

Expanding on the Analysis¶

I think the bike data could help us asses equity, although there is so much more that can be done as this dataset is pretty limited. We need to analyze the ridesharing dynamics across different neighborhoods with different demographics, we also could look at data from other cities and see what patterns do overlap across them. We could take a look at the race and gender of the registered users and also look what type of places do the users usually tend to go; commute? parks? groceries? -- There is so much that can still be done.

Now, Bike sharing is growing in popularity and new cities and regions are making efforts to implement bike sharing systems that complement their other transportation offerings. The goals of these efforts are to have bike sharing serve as an alternate form of transportation in order to alleviate congestion, provide geographic connectivity, reduce carbon emissions, and promote inclusion among communities.

Bike sharing systems have spread to many cities across the country. The company you work for asks you to determine the feasibility of expanding bike sharing to additional cities of the U.S.

Based on your plots in this project I would recommend to have bike stations available at the most dense workplaces. This could have now changed due to the pandemic and remote working, but in general the plots show that during the weekdays most users are riding for commuting, and one can assume to work.

I would also recommend to have enough bikes for the weekends, specifically Thursday/Friday that is when casual riders begin to peak, and this could disturb the bike availabity for these that commute on a daily basis, or at least during the weekdays
